log.scrcivf.com/embryo-transfer-tips-for-before-and-after-the-procedure\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.scrcivf.com%2Fembryo-transfer-tips-for-before-and-after-the-procedure&d=Nfsz5E3m9Y1rIgqi3P%2FNwKWGW%2FHqnCni%2B1xW1zXhD2s%3D&h=db550d13\" target=\"_blank\">https://blog.scrcivf.com/embryo-transfer-tips-for-before-and-after-the-procedure</a><br />\n<br />\nWhat is embryo implantation?<br />\nImplantation occurs when an embryo attaches to the wall of the uterus in the endometrial lining. In IVF, it occurs six to ten days after the egg retrieval process, which is one to five days after the embryo transfer. This equates to days 20 to 24 of an ideal 28 day menstrual cycle.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Avoid extremes of temperature<br />\nHot tubs, saunas, hot yoga, or any activity that raises your internal temperature is something to avoid at this point. In general it&rsquo;s best not to be submerged in water such as pools or baths during this time, as it leaves you vulnerable to infection. Stick to a soothing hot shower until your doctor tells you otherwise.</strong><br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/forums/index.php?/topic/895425-having-a-bath-and-swimming-after-embryo-transfer/\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.essentialbaby.com.au%2Fforums%2Findex.php%3F%2Ftopic%2F895425-having-a-bath-and-swimming-after-embryo-transfer%2F&d=Nfsz5E3m9Y1rIgqi3P%2FNwKWGW%2FHqnCni%2B1xW1zXhD2s%3D&h=7475a62c\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/forums/index.php?/topic/895425-having-a-bath-and-swimming-after-embryo-transfer/</a><br />\n<br />\n<strong>Hi PriLou,<br />\n<br />\nMy clinic advises no tub baths or swimming for 48 hours post embryo transfer. <br />\n<br />\nI'm guessing that after that is fine as long as you don't increase your core temp, so no hot baths or training for the olympic swim team<br />\n<br />\n</strong>"},{"pid":"4efef4d65fd9e8497de3d80dbdf26dddff370814","tid":961123,"uid":135